  "event_preview": "Martinsville Speedway is a 0.526-mile (0.847 km) oval in Ridgeway, Virginia, shaped like a paperclip — two long flat straights connected by tight, heavily-braked concrete-paved turns with just 12 degrees of banking. Founded in 1947 by H. Clay Earles, it is the only track to have hosted NASCAR Cup Series races every year since the division's inception in 1949 — a record no other venue on the calendar can match. The Cook Out 400 is the seventh race of the 2026 season and the first true short track event of the year. Racing here is an exercise in attrition, aggression and patience in equal measure — track position is king, the walls are always close, and contact is not so much a risk as a certainty. The winner receives not a conventional trophy but a grandfather clock — a tradition dating back to 1964, a nod to Martinsville's heritage as the furniture capital of Virginia. The all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Joey Logano, who set a 18.898-second lap in March 2014, while the all-time fastest lap in race conditions — 18.845 seconds, set by Ross Chastain on the final lap of the 2022 fall race — remains one of the most extraordinary laps in NASCAR history."
}
